ervice, part of that service is to protect your customers from the negative impacts associated with that service. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Can I sue someone if my friend has a problem at a pool and has to go to the hospital? The pool was without a lifeguard, but they happen to have a sign that says no lifeguard on duty.<br>
<br>
How is this any different? <p><hr><center>Cracked eggs, dead birds<BR>Scream as they fight for life<BR>I can feel death, can see its beady eyes<BR>All these things into position<BR>All these things we'll one day swallow whole<BR>
And fade out again...</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=calonderiel@firionavie>Calonderiel</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_whitespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/21/03 12:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=931.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;OH-NO!&quot; - say's Bill Gates</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you provide a service, part of that service is to protect your customers from the negative impacts associated with that service. <br>
<br>
A company making tin cans needs to ensure that they take reasonable steps to prevent those tin cans causing harm, such as providing safe opening devices, using the correct non toxic material and solder etc.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>*sigh*</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> This is promoting the &quot;babysit the idiot&quot; attitude that is pervading modern culture. People - consumers - are all too keen to place blame at manufacturers' doorsteps, attempting to absolve themselves of guilt by claiming utter idiocy and ignorance of the most basic concepts of common sense.<br>
<br>
There are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>hundreds</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of possible ways in which online chat rooms could be used for criminal or morally corrupt practices, and there are a thousand other minor potential risks. Microsoft <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>cannot</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> warn their users of every single possible risk associated with using a chat room. Their disclaimer would read like War And Peace:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Please be aware that:<br>
- Your children may be at risk from paedophiles;<br>
- You may be at risk from sexual predators;<br>
- You may be at risk of cult brainwashing;<br>
- You may be at risk of becoming addicted to chat rooms;<br>
- You may be at risk from identity thieves;<br>
- You may be at risk of someone giving away the end to that new suspense thriller movie you wanted to go see at the theatre;<br>
- You may be at risk of hearing offensive language;<br>
- You may be at risk of hearing prejudiced opinions;<br>
- You may be at risk of being told blue jokes;<br>
- You may be at risk of making strong friendships which, through a freak sequence of events, are broken after several years, leaving you with the cost of high medical bills for psychological support after the loss of friendship sinks you into deep depression;<br>
- You may be at risk from eye strain<br>
....</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
It's impractical. More than that, it's bloody stupid. A company making tin cans doesn't say:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Do not eat this tin can&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->,<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Do not attempt to insert this tin can into bodily orifices&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, or<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Do not throw yourself from the top of the Empire State Building clutching this upturned tin can in the hope that it will act as an adequate parachute&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
All companies assume that customers will employ <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>some</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> degree of common sense and responsibility in the application of their products or services. Sadly, such cases as the suing of McDonalds for failing to mark their hot coffee as &quot;hot&quot; highlight the current trend towards crediting the average consumer with an IQ less than that of a raspberry pop-tart.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Microsoft also needs to ensure that its service is relatively safe<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I'm sure they do. I'm sure they put in place all the appropriate procedures and safeguards to protect their customers' computers from getting viruses, from IP traces and DoS attacks, from release of sensitive real-life information. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>That</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is Microsoft's responsibility, if anything. I'm Microsoft <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>does</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have a disclaimer in place, and I'm sure it requires chat room users to accept, amongst other rules, that users may not conduct illegal or improper practises via the chatrooms, and that minors must have the consent or supervision of a parent or guardian. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>That</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is MS doing their part. The chatrooms are offered &quot;as-is&quot; - as a medium for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>unmoderated</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> chat. If MS customers choose to abuse the regulations that MS put in place - by 'grooming' small children or, in the case of parents/guardians, by allowing the minor in their care to use the chatroom unsupervised - then MS cannot be held responsible.<br>
<br>
It's solely the lack of care and attention on the part of the parent that is responsible for putting children at risk of paedophile attention. Why should Microsoft be responsible for supervising other people's children? That's the parents' job!!<br>
<br>
As far as the pro-Microsoft spin on the topic goes -- why not? Good for them. It puts a positive angle on what is otherwise an entirely negative subject. Let's face it, if people are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>that</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> concerned that MS chatrooms are a source of paedophile action, then they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>are</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> doing the general public a favour by closing them down. If MS had wanted to be absolutely truthful, their press release would simply have said: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;We've decided to close down all our chatrooms, as we cannot afford the expense of adding moderators simply because a bunch of lazy parents can't be bothered to supervise their own kids.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> And if they had added moderators to the chatrooms, you just know it would have turned into an 'Big Brother/invasion of privacy' and 'restricting freedom of speech' issue.<br>
